key_points: Gabby Petito starred in a music video about gun violence and violence against children titled "Irreplaceable" eight years before her death.
The music video was released by Deb Henson, a Long Island-based singer and songwriter, a year after the 2012 Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting.
Gabby Petito appeared in the video at age 14 with her stepbrothers, holding a sign that read "I'm irreplaceable".
Deb Henson shared her feelings on watching the video after Petito's death, noting the profound impact and heartbreak it caused her.
Henson praised Gabby's bright personality and spirit during the production of the music video.
The song and music video have been rededicated in honor of Gabby Petito, with proceeds from downloads donated to the Gabby Petito Foundation.
Gabby's body was found in Grand Teton National Park and identified on September 19, confirming her death was a homicide.
Brian Laundrie, Gabby's fiancé, is named a person of interest in her death and is subject to a massive manhunt.
A nationwide demand for answers has emerged due to the mystery and unusual details surrounding Petito's case and death.
The FBI is seeking information related to Brian Laundrie's role in the matter and his current whereabouts.
spokespersons: Michael Schneider (Special Agent in Charge, FBI)
